Best Practices Summary:

Write unit tests first — if you need Spring context to test a class, it is a design smell, consider splitting responsibilities
Use test slices (@WebMvcTest, @DataJpaTest) instead of @SpringBootTest wherever possible — they are 5–10x faster
Never use production DB for tests — always H2, Testcontainers, or a dedicated test schema
One assertion concept per test — do not test 10 things in one @Test method
Name tests clearly — methodName_shouldExpectedBehavior_whenCondition pattern is readable and self-documenting
Avoid @DirtiesContext — it kills context cache and makes suites slow; redesign the test instead
Keep @MockBean usage minimal in integration tests — if you mock everything, you are not integrating anything
Use @Transactional on test classes for auto-rollback — avoids manual cleanup SQL
Separate application-test.yml for test-specific config — never override production properties inline in 20 test classes
Test the unhappy path as much as the happy path — null inputs, empty results, exceptions, timeout scenarios
Use AssertJ over JUnit assertions — assertThat(x).isEqualTo(y) gives far better failure messages than assertEquals(y, x)
Run Testcontainers tests in CI only — mark them with a custom tag and skip locally for speed
